quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Defining a Function[/h1]

To define a JavaScript function, use the [b]function [/b]keyword, followed by a [b]name[/b], followed by a set of [b]parentheses ()[/b].

The code to be executed by the function is placed inside curly brackets {}.[code format="js"][b]function [/b]name() {    
  //code to be executed
}[/code]
[note]Function names can contain letters, digits, underscores, and dollar signs (same rules as variables).[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to define and call the "hello" function.
[!raw!]
{0} hello() {
   alert("Hi there");
}
{1}();

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Calling a Function[/h1]

To execute the function, you need to call it.
To call a function, start with the name of the function, then follow it with the arguments in parentheses.
[b]Example:[/b] [code format="js" codeId="675"]function [b]myFunction[/b]() {
  alert("Calling a Function!");
}

[b]myFunction[/b]();
//Alerts "Calling a Function!"[/code]
[note]Always remember to end the statement with a [b]semicolon [/b]after calling the function.[/note]

[h1]Calling Functions[/h1]

Once the function is defined, JavaScript allows you to call it as many times as you want to.[code format="js" codeId="676"]function myFunction() {
   alert("Alert box!");
}

myFunction();
//"Alert box!"

// some other code

myFunction();
//"Alert box!"[/code]
